var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#dev_docs","page":"Developer documentation","text":"note: Contributing guidelines\n\n\nIf you haven't, please read the Contributing guidelines first.\n\nIf you want to make contributions to this package that involves code, then this guide is for you.","title":"Developer documentation"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#First-time-clone","page":"Developer documentation","text":"tip: If you have writing rights\n\n\nIf you have writing rights, you don't have to fork. Instead, simply clone and skip ahead. Whenever upstream is mentioned, use origin instead.\n\nIf this is the first time you work with this repository, follow the instructions below to clone the repository.\n\nFork this repo\nClone your repo (this will create a git remote called origin)\nAdd this repo as a remote:\ngit remote add upstream https://github.com/JuliaXRTS/ElectronicStructureModels.jl\n\nThis will ensure that you have two remotes in your git: origin and upstream. You will create branches and push to origin, and you will fetch and update your local main branch from upstream.","title":"First time clone"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Linting-and-formatting","page":"Developer documentation","text":"Install a plugin on your editor to use EditorConfig. This will ensure that your editor is configured with important formatting settings.\n\nWe use https://pre-commit.com to run the linters and formatters. In particular, the Julia code is formatted using JuliaFormatter.jl, so please install it globally first:\n\njulia> # Press ]\npkg> activate\npkg> add JuliaFormatter\n\nTo install pre-commit, we recommend using pipx as follows:\n\n# Install pipx following the link\npipx install pre-commit\n\nWith pre-commit installed, activate it as a pre-commit hook:\n\npre-commit install\n\nTo run the linting and formatting manually, enter the command below:\n\npre-commit run -a\n\nNow, you can only commit if all the pre-commit tests pass.","title":"Linting and formatting"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Testing","page":"Developer documentation","text":"As with most Julia packages, you can just open Julia in the repository folder, activate the environment, and run test:\n\njulia> # press ]\npkg> activate .\npkg> test","title":"Testing"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Working-on-a-new-issue","page":"Developer documentation","text":"We try to keep a linear history in this repo, so it is important to keep your branches up-to-date.\n\nFetch from the remote and fast-forward your local main\ngit fetch upstream\ngit switch main\ngit merge --ff-only upstream/main\nBranch from main to address the issue (see below for naming)\ngit switch -c 42-add-answer-universe\nPush the new local branch to your personal remote repository\ngit push -u origin 42-add-answer-universe\nCreate a pull request to merge your remote branch into the org main.","title":"Working on a new issue"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Branch-naming","page":"Developer documentation","text":"If there is an associated issue, add the issue number.\nIf there is no associated issue, and the changes are small, add a prefix such as \"typo\", \"hotfix\", \"small-refactor\", according to the type of update.\nIf the changes are not small and there is no associated issue, then create the issue first, so we can properly discuss the changes.\nUse dash separated imperative wording related to the issue (e.g., 14-add-tests, 15-fix-model, 16-remove-obsolete-files).","title":"Branch naming"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Commit-message","page":"Developer documentation","text":"Use imperative or present tense, for instance: Add feature or Fix bug.\nHave informative titles.\nWhen necessary, add a body with details.\nIf there are breaking changes, add the information to the commit message.","title":"Commit message"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Before-creating-a-pull-request","page":"Developer documentation","text":"tip: Atomic git commits\n\n\nTry to create \"atomic git commits\" (recommended reading: The Utopic Git History).\n\nMake sure the tests pass.\nMake sure the pre-commit tests pass.\nFetch any main updates from upstream and rebase your branch, if necessary:\ngit fetch upstream\ngit rebase upstream/main BRANCH_NAME\nThen you can open a pull request and work with the reviewer to address any issues.","title":"Before creating a pull request"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Building-and-viewing-the-documentation-locally","page":"Developer documentation","text":"Following the latest suggestions, we recommend using LiveServer to build the documentation. Here is how you do it:\n\nRun julia --project=docs to open Julia in the environment of the docs.\nIf this is the first time building the docs\nPress ] to enter pkg mode\nRun pkg> dev . to use the development version of your package\nPress backspace to leave pkg mode\nRun julia> using LiveServer\nRun julia> servedocs()","title":"Building and viewing the documentation locally"},{"category":"section","location":"91-developer/#Making-a-new-release","page":"Developer documentation","text":"To create a new release, you can follow these simple steps:\n\nCreate a branch release-x.y.z\nUpdate version in Project.toml\nUpdate the CHANGELOG.md:\nRename the section \"Unreleased\" to \"[x.y.z] - yyyy-mm-dd\" (i.e., version under brackets, dash, and date in ISO format)\nAdd a new section on top of it named \"Unreleased\"\nAdd a new link in the bottom for version \"x.y.z\"\nChange the \"[unreleased]\" link to use the latest version - end of line, vx.y.z ... HEAD.\nCreate a commit \"Release vx.y.z\", push, create a PR, wait for it to pass, merge the PR.\nGo back to main screen and click on the latest commit (link: https://github.com/JuliaXRTS/ElectronicStructureModels.jl/commit/main)\nAt the bottom, write @JuliaRegistrator register\n\nAfter that, you only need to wait and verify:\n\nWait for the bot to comment (should take < 1m) with a link to a PR to the registry\nFollow the link and wait for a comment on the auto-merge\nThe comment should said all is well and auto-merge should occur shortly\nAfter the merge happens, TagBot will trigger and create a new GitHub tag. Check on https://github.com/JuliaXRTS/ElectronicStructureModels.jl/releases\nAfter the release is create, a \"docs\" GitHub action will start for the tag.\nAfter it passes, a deploy action will run.\nAfter that runs, the stable docs should be updated. Check them and look for the version number.","title":"Making a new release"},{"category":"section","location":"95-reference/#reference","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Reference"},{"category":"section","location":"95-reference/#Contents","page":"Reference","text":"Pages = [\"95-reference.md\"]","title":"Contents"},{"category":"section","location":"95-reference/#Index","page":"Reference","text":"Pages = [\"95-reference.md\"]","title":"Index"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractElectronSystem","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractElectronSystem <: AbstractMatterModel\n\nAbstract base type for electron matter models.\n\nInterface requirements\n\nConcrete subtypes must implement the following functions:\n\nMatter model interface:\n\n_number_density(sys::AbstractElectronSystem)::Real\n_temperature(sys::AbstractElectronSystem)::Real\n\nElectronic system interface:\n\nimag_dynamic_response(sys::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::NTuple{2, Real})::Real\nreal_dynamic_response(sys::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::NTuple{2, Real})::Real\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractElectronSystem"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractInteractingElectronSystem","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractInteractingElectronSystem\n\nAbstract base type for electronic system with interacting electrons by introducing screening potentials. Interface functions to be implemented are:\n\nMatter model interface:\nelectron_density(::AbstractElectronSystem)::Real\ntemperature(::AbstractElectronSystem)::Real\nElectronic system interface:\nimag_dynamic_response(::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::NTuple{2,Real})::Real\n`realdynamicresponse(::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::\nInteracting electronic system interface:\nproper_electron_system(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)::AbstractProperElectronSystem\nscreening(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)::AbstractScreening\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractInteractingElectronSystem"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractIonSystem","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractIonSystem <: AbstractPlasmaComponent\n\nAbstract base type representing an ion component of a Chihara plasma.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractIonSystem"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractIonicFormFactor","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractIonicFormFactor\n\nAbstract base type for ionic form factor approximations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractIonicFormFactor"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractMatterModel","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractMatterModel\n\nAbstract base type representing a generic matter model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractMatterModel"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractPlasmaComponent","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractPlasmaComponent\n\nAbstract base type representing components of a plasma described by the Chihara model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractPlasmaComponent"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractScreening","page":"Reference","text":"AbstractScreening\n\nAbstract base type for screening models. Interface functions, which must be implemented:\n\npseudo_potential(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)::AbstractPseudoPotential\nlocal_field_correction(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)::AbstractLocalFieldCorrection\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.AbstractScreening"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.CoulombPseudoPotential","page":"Reference","text":"CoulombPseudoPotential <: AbstractPseudoPotential\n\nRepresents the bare Coulomb pseudo potential: V(q) = e² / q².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.CoulombPseudoPotential"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable","page":"Reference","text":"GridLookupTable(\n    cols::T1,\n    rows::T2,\n    values::T3\n) where {T1<:AbstractVector{T},T2<:AbstractVector{T},T3<:AbstractMatrix{T}} where {T<:Real}\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.IdealElectronSystem","page":"Reference","text":"IdealElectronSystem{T, A} <: AbstractIdealElectronSystem\n\nRepresents a non-interacting (ideal) electron system, parameterized by a numerical type (T) and a response approximation model (A). The system may be used to model either a finite-temperature or an effective zero-temperature electron gas. The latter is obtained by choosing approx = ZeroTemperatureApprox().\n\nType Parameters\n\nT <: Real: Internal numeric type (e.g. Float64).\nA <: AbstractResponseApproximation: Approximation model used for the response function (e.g. NoApprox() or ZeroTemperatureApprox()).\n\nFields\n\nelectron_density::T: Electron number density (stored in atomic units).\ntemperature::T: Temperature (stored in atomic units).\napprox::A: Approximation model for the response function.\n\nConstructors\n\nIdealElectronSystem(electron_density::T1, temperature::T2, approx::A)\n\nConstruct an ideal electron system with a given electron density, temperature, and response approximation model.\n\nIdealElectronSystem(electron_density::T1, approx::ZeroTemperatureApprox)\n\nConstruct an effectively zero-temperature system.\n\nIdealElectronSystem(electron_density::T1, temperature::T2)\n\nConstruct an ideal electron system using the default response approximation (NoApprox()).\n\nExamples\n\n```julia using Unitful\n\nZero-temperature system\n\nsys1 = IdealElectronSystem(1e23u\"cm^(-3)\", ZeroTemperatureApprox())\n\nFinite-temperature system with explicit approximation\n\nsys2 = IdealElectronSystem(1e23u\"cm^(-3)\", 300.0u\"K\", NonDegenerated())\n\nFinite-temperature system with default approximation\n\nsys3 = IdealElectronSystem(1e23u\"cm^(-3)\", 300.0u\"K\")\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.IdealElectronSystem"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.InteractingElectronSystem","page":"Reference","text":"InteractingElectronSystem{PES, S} <: AbstractInteractingElectronSystem\n\nRepresents an interacting electron system consisting of a proper electron system (e.g., a free or ideal Fermi gas) and a screening model that modifies its response.\n\nType Parameters\n\nPES <: AbstractProperElectronSystem: Type of the proper (non-interacting) electron system.\nS <: AbstractScreening: Type of the screening model.\n\nFields\n\nproper_elec_system::PES: The underlying proper electron system.\nscreening::S: The screening model used to compute interactions.\n\nConstructors\n\nInteractingElectronSystem(pelsys::PES, scr::S)\n\nConstruct an interacting electron system directly from a proper electron system and a screening model.\n\nInteractingElectronSystem{PES}(electron_density::T1, temp::T2, scr::S)\n\nConstruct an interacting system by providing physical parameters, where PES is the desired proper electron system type.\n\nExamples\n\niesys = InteractingElectronSystem{IdealFermiGas}(1e23, 300.0, Screening())\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.InteractingElectronSystem"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.NoLocalFieldCorrection","page":"Reference","text":"NoLocalFieldCorrection <: AbstractLocalFieldCorrection\n\nRepresents a model with no local field correction (i.e., the correction is zero).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.NoLocalFieldCorrection"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.NoScreening","page":"Reference","text":"NoScreening <: AbstractScreening\n\nA screening model with no dielectric screening; dielectric function is unity, and corrections vanish.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.NoScreening"},{"category":"type","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.Screening","page":"Reference","text":"Screening{PP, LFC} <: AbstractScreening\n\nA general screening model that combines a pseudo potential and a local field correction.\n\nFields\n\npseudo_potential: An instance of AbstractPseudoPotential.\nlfc: An instance of AbstractLocalFieldCorrection.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.Screening"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._dielectric_function-Tuple{Number, Number}","page":"Reference","text":"dielectric_function(::AbstractIdealElectronSystem,::AbstractScreening,om_q)\n\nReturn the value of the dielectric function for the given proper response function and given local effective potential.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._dielectric_function"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._imag_ideal_dynamic_response","page":"Reference","text":"_imag_ideal_dynamic_response(\n    sys::AbstractIdealElectronSystem,\n    approx::AbstractResponseApproximation,\n    ombar::T,\n    qbar::T\n) where {T<:Real}\n\nCompute the imaginary part of the dynamic response function of an ideal electron system using the given response approximation. The input frequencies ombar and wavevectors qbar are given in dimensionless units (normalized to Fermi energy and Fermi wavevector, respectively).\n\nThis is a low-level method, typically implemented by concrete approximation types.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._imag_ideal_dynamic_response"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._number_density","page":"Reference","text":"_number_density(comp::AbstractPlasmaComponent)\n\nInterface function: return the number density parameter of the plasma component.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._number_density"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._real_ideal_dynamic_response","page":"Reference","text":"real_ideal_dynamic_response(\n    sys::AbstractIdealElectronSystem,\n    approx::AbstractResponseApproximation,\n    ombar::T,\n    qbar::T\n) where {T<:Real}\n\nCompute the real part of the dynamic response function of an ideal electron system using the given response approximation. The input frequencies ombar and wavevectors qbar are given in dimensionless units (normalized to Fermi energy and Fermi wavevector, respectively).\n\nThis is a low-level interface meant for implementation by specific approximation models.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._real_ideal_dynamic_response"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._stable_log_term-Tuple{Real}","page":"Reference","text":"_stable_log_term(x::Real)\n\nStable version of\n\nlogleft(leftvertfrac1+x1-xrightvertright)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._stable_log_term"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels._temperature","page":"Reference","text":"_temperature(comp::AbstractPlasmaComponent)\n\nInterface function: return the temperature parameter of the plasma component.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels._temperature"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.atomic_number","page":"Reference","text":"atomic_number(ions::AbstractIonSystem)\n\nInterface function: return the atomic number of a given ion system. That is the number of protons in the nucleus of the ion: Z_A.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.atomic_number"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.beta-Tuple{AbstractElectronSystem}","page":"Reference","text":"beta(esys::AbstractElectronSystem) -> Real\n\nCompute the inverse temperature β = 1 / T of the system esys.\n\nArguments\n\nesys: An instance of AbstractElectronSystem representing the electronic system.\n\nReturns\n\nInverse temperature β as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.beta"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.betabar-Tuple{AbstractElectronSystem}","page":"Reference","text":"betabar(esys::AbstractElectronSystem) -> Real\n\nCompute the dimensionless inverse temperature barbeta= E_F  T of the system esys.\n\nArguments\n\nesys: An instance of AbstractElectronSystem representing the electronic system.\n\nReturns\n\nDimensionless inverse temperature β̄ as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.betabar"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"dielectric_function(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Real\n\nDelegates to the dielectric_function using the proper electron system and screening model associated with iesys.\n\nArguments\n\niesys: An interacting electron system.\nom_q: Tuple (ω, q) representing frequency and wavevector magnitude.\n\nReturns\n\nDielectric function ϵ(q, ω) as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractProperElectronSystem, AbstractScreening, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"dielectric_function(::AbstractIdealElectronSystem,::AbstractScreening,om_q)\n\nReturn the value of the dielectric function for the given electron system and given screening.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractProperElectronSystem, NoScreening, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"dielectric_function(esys, scr::NoScreening, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the dielectric function for a NoScreening model, which is always 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.dielectric_function"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.dynamic_response-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"dynamic_response(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Complex\n\nCompute the dynamically screened response function of the interacting electron system.\n\nThe response is computed as\n\nχ(q ω) = fracχ_0(q ω)ϵ(q ω)\n\nwhere χ₀ is the proper response and ϵ is the dielectric function derived from the screening model.\n\nArguments\n\niesys: An interacting electron system.\nom_q: Tuple (ω, q) representing frequency and wavevector magnitude.\n\nReturns\n\nComplex-valued dynamic response χ(q, ω).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.dynamic_response"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.fermi_energy-Tuple{AbstractElectronSystem}","page":"Reference","text":"fermi_energy(esys::AbstractElectronSystem) -> Real\n\nCompute the Fermi energy of a given electronic system esys, using its Fermi wave vector.\n\nArguments\n\nesys: An instance of AbstractElectronSystem representing the electronic system.\n\nReturns\n\nFermi energy EF as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.fermi_energy"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.fermi_wave_vector-Tuple{AbstractElectronSystem}","page":"Reference","text":"fermi_wave_vector(esys::AbstractElectronSystem) -> Real\n\nCompute the Fermi wave vector for a given electronic system esys, based on its electron density.\n\nArguments\n\nesys: An instance of AbstractElectronSystem representing the electronic system.\n\nReturns\n\nFermi wave vector kF as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.fermi_wave_vector"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.form_factor","page":"Reference","text":"form_factor(ions::AbstractIonSystem, approx::AbstractFormFactor, q::Real)\n\nInterface function: return the ionic form factor for a given ion system and a given form factor approximation/strategy. Detault for the latter is PaulingShermanFormFactor().\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.form_factor"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.imag_dynamic_response","page":"Reference","text":"imag_dynamic_response(sys::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::NTuple{2, T}) where {T<:Real}\n\nReturn the imaginary part of the dynamic response function for the given electron system sys at frequency and wavevector specified by om_q = (ω, q).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.imag_dynamic_response"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.imag_dynamic_response-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"imag_dynamic_response(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the imaginary part of the dynamic response function of the interacting electron system.\n\nReturns\n\nImaginary part of χ(q, ω).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.imag_dynamic_response"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.ionization_state","page":"Reference","text":"ionization_state(ions::AbstractIonSystem)\n\nInterface function: return the ionizationstate of a given ion system. That is the net electric charge in units of the elementary charge, i.e. number of protons minus number of bound electrons: ``ZF = ZA - ZB``. This is also referred to as the number of free electrons per ion.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.ionization_state"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.local_effective_potential-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"local_effective_potential(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Real\n\nDelegates to the local_effective_potential method of the screening model associated with iesys.\n\nArguments\n\niesys: An interacting electron system.\nom_q: Tuple (ω, q) representing frequency and wavevector magnitude.\n\nReturns\n\nLocal effective potential V_eff(q, ω) as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.local_effective_potential"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.local_effective_potential-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{NoScreening, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"local_effective_potential(scr::NoScreening, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the local effective potential for the NoScreening model, which is zero.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.local_effective_potential"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.local_field_correction","page":"Reference","text":"local_field_correction(::AbstractScreening, om_q::Tuple)\n\nInterface function: return value of the local field correction for interacting electron systems\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.local_field_correction"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.local_field_correction-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{NoScreening, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"local_field_correction(scr::NoScreening, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the local field correction for the NoScreening model, which is zero.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.local_field_correction"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.lookup-Tuple{ElectronicStructureModels.AboveInput, Real, Real, ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable}","page":"Reference","text":"lookup(\nmethod::AboveInput,\ncolumn::Real,\nrow::Real,\ntable::GridLookupTable)\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.lookup"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.lookup-Tuple{ElectronicStructureModels.BelowInput, Real, Real, ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable}","page":"Reference","text":"lookup(\nmethod::BelowInput,\ncolumn::Real,\nrow::Real,\ntable::GridLookupTable)\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.lookup"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.lookup-Tuple{ElectronicStructureModels.InterpolEndValue, Real, Real, ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable}","page":"Reference","text":"lookup(\nmethod::InterpolEndValue,\ncolumn::Real,\nrow::Real,\ntable::GridLookupTable)\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.lookup"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.lookup-Tuple{ElectronicStructureModels.InterpolExtrapol, Real, Real, ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable}","page":"Reference","text":"lookup(\nmethod::InterpolExtrapol,\ncolumn::Real,\nrow::Real,\ntable::GridLookupTable)\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.lookup"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.lookup-Tuple{ElectronicStructureModels.NearestInput, Real, Real, ElectronicStructureModels.GridLookupTable}","page":"Reference","text":"lookup(\nmethod::NearestInput,\ncolumn::Real,\nrow::Real,\ntable::GridLookupTable)\n\nTBW\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.lookup"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.number_bound_electrons","page":"Reference","text":"number_bound_electrons(ions::AbstractIonSystem)\n\nInterface function: return the number of bound electrons of a given ion system. That is the number of protons minus the ionization state: Z_B = Z_A - Z_F.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.number_bound_electrons"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.proper_electron_system","page":"Reference","text":"proper_electron_system(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)\n\nInterface function: return the proper electron system associated with the interacting system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.proper_electron_system"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential","page":"Reference","text":"pseudo_potential(::AbstractScreening, om_q::Tuple)\n\nInterface function: return value of the pseudo potential for interacting electron systems\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"pseudo_potential(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Real\n\nDelegates to the pseudo_potential method of the screening model associated with iesys.\n\nArguments\n\niesys: An interacting electron system.\nom_q: Tuple (ω, q) representing frequency and wavevector magnitude.\n\nReturns\n\nPseudo potential V(q, ω) as a real number.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{NoScreening, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"pseudo_potential(scr::NoScreening, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the pseudo potential for the NoScreening model, which is zero.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.pseudo_potential"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.real_dynamic_response","page":"Reference","text":"real_dynamic_response(sys::AbstractElectronSystem, om_q::NTuple{2, T}) where {T<:Real}\n\nReturn the real part of the dynamic response function for the given electron system sys at frequency and wavevector specified by om_q = (ω, q).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.real_dynamic_response"},{"category":"method","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.real_dynamic_response-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, Tuple{T, T}}} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"real_dynamic_response(iesys::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem, om_q) -> Real\n\nReturn the real part of the dynamic response function of the interacting electron system.\n\nReturns\n\nReal part of χ(q, ω).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.real_dynamic_response"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.response_approximation","page":"Reference","text":"response_approximation(sys::AbstractIdealElectronSystem)\n\nReturn the response approximation model associated with the given ideal electron system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.response_approximation"},{"category":"function","location":"95-reference/#ElectronicStructureModels.screening","page":"Reference","text":"screening(::AbstractInteractingElectronSystem)\n\nInterface function: return the screening associated with the interacting system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.screening"},{"category":"section","location":"90-contributing/#contributing","page":"Contributing guidelines","text":"First of all, thanks for the interest!\n\nWe welcome all kinds of contribution, including, but not limited to code, documentation, examples, configuration, issue creating, etc.\n\nBe polite and respectful, and follow the code of conduct.","title":"Contributing guidelines"},{"category":"section","location":"90-contributing/#Bug-reports-and-discussions","page":"Contributing guidelines","text":"If you think you found a bug, feel free to open an issue. Focused suggestions and requests can also be opened as issues. Before opening a pull request, start an issue or a discussion on the topic, please.","title":"Bug reports and discussions"},{"category":"section","location":"90-contributing/#Working-on-an-issue","page":"Contributing guidelines","text":"If you found an issue that interests you, comment on that issue what your plans are. If the solution to the issue is clear, you can immediately create a pull request (see below). Otherwise, say what your proposed solution is and wait for a discussion around it.\n\ntip: Tip\n\n\nFeel free to ping us after a few days if there are no responses.\n\nIf your solution involves code (or something that requires running the package locally), check the developer documentation. Otherwise, you can use the GitHub interface directly to create your pull request.","title":"Working on an issue"},{"category":"section","location":"#ElectronicStructureModels.jl","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"(Image: Stable Documentation) (Image: Development documentation) (Image: Test workflow status) (Image: BestieTemplate) (Image: code style: runic)","title":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Overview","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl is an open-source Julia package providing models from electronic-structure theory for use in larger simulations and data analysis workflows. It is designed with a focus on applications in X-ray Thomson Scattering (XRTS), but the components are general enough to be used in a broader context involving electron-gas models and response functions.","title":"Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"#Key-Features","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"The package currently includes:\n\nDynamic structure factors (DSF) for the uniform electron gas; including the finite-temperature Lindhard function within the Random Phase Approximation (RPA)\nSeveral approximation levels for evaluating DSF and related quantities\nA clean, extensible interface for adding new electronic-structure models in the future","title":"Key Features"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"The package is not registered yet. To install it locally:\n\ngit clone https://github.com/JuliaXRTS/ElectronicStructureModels.jl.git\ncd ElectronicStructureModels.jl\njulia --project -e \"import Pkg; Pkg.build()\"\n\nThen in Julia:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.activate(\".\")\nPkg.instantiate()\n\nThis will also install required dependencies such as Unitful.jl.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Quickstart-Example","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"Below is a minimal example showing how to construct an electron system and compute a dynamic structure factor. The example uses CairoMakie for plotting, but any plotting backend can be used.\n\nusing ElectronicStructureModels\nusing Unitful\nusing CairoMakie\n\nNE   = 10e23u\"cm^(-3)\"   # electron density\nTEMP = 1.0u\"eV\"          # temperature\n\nideal = IdealElectronSystem(NE, TEMP) # idear proper system\nesys  = InteractingElectronSystem(ideal, Screening()) # RPA screening model\n\nKF = fermi_wave_vector(esys) # Fermi wave vector (for scaling)\nEF = fermi_energy(esys) # Fermi energy (for scaling)\n\nω_arr = range(1e-4, 6, 100) .* EF # array of energy transfer values\nq     = 1.6 * KF # momentum transfer value\n\n# calculation of the DSF\ndsf_values = [dynamic_structure_factor(esys, (ω, q)) for ω in ω_arr]\n\n\n# Plotting of the DSF as a function of the energy transfer normalized to unit height.\nfig = Figure()\nax  = Axis(fig[1,1])\n\nnorm = maximum(dsf_values)\nlines!(ax, ω_arr ./ EF, dsf_values ./ norm)\n\ndisplay(fig)","title":"Quickstart Example"},{"category":"section","location":"#Contributing","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"Contributions of all kinds are welcome. Please read the contributing guide or its rendered version in the online documentation before opening pull requests or issues.","title":"Contributing"},{"category":"section","location":"#Credits-and-Funding","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"This work has been partially supported by the Center for Advanced Systems Understanding (CASUS), funded by the German Federal Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF) and the Saxon Ministry for Science, Culture and Tourism (SMWK) with tax funds based on the budget approved by the Saxon State Parliament.","title":"Credits and Funding"},{"category":"section","location":"#Acknowledgements","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"Special thanks to Tobias Dornheim for funding, valuable input and support.","title":"Acknowledgements"},{"category":"section","location":"#License","page":"ElectronicStructureModels.jl","text":"MIT © Uwe Hernandez Acosta","title":"License"}]
}
